properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A major low pressure system from the Great Lakes will affect the province of Quebec on Thursday and Friday. This system could give the first significant amounts of snow over Northwestern and Central Quebec. Snowfall amounts could exceed 15 centimetres in several areas. properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: First significant snowfall of the season possibly Thursday night into Friday. A strong low pressure system will approach Ontario from the southwest. Snow may arrive Thursday evening then continue through the night before tapering off by Friday afternoon. Snowfall amounts of 10 to 20 cm are possible. Motorists should be prepared for poor winter driving conditions, and adjust travel plans accordingly. There is some uncertainty in the track of this low pressure system and the amount of snowfall expected. This event will continue to be closely monitored. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: First accumulating snowfall of the season may herald the arrival of November. A low pressure system will approach Ontario from the southwest. This weather system will bring a significant rainfall with it tonight through Thursday with many areas receiving a total of 20 to 40 mm of rain by Thursday evening. As the low passes by Thursday night, rain may change over to snow before tapering off Friday. Snowfall amounts of 2 to 4 cm are possible. There is uncertainty in the track of the low, which will affect how quickly the rain will change over to snow and subsequent snowfall amounts. Some folks may wake up to snow covered grass for the first time this season Friday morning. This event will continue to be monitored. Poor winter driving conditions are possible Thursday night. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Summary:

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: First major snowfall of the season Halloween Night. Rain or mixed precipitation will arrive by Thursday morning then change over to snow by Thursday evening. Snow may become heavy at times Thursday night, and may also become mixed with ice pellets especially in the North Bay area. Snow is expected to taper off on Friday. Total snowfall amounts near 15 cm are expected across the region, with a few locally higher amounts up to 25 cm possible especially near the Quebec Border. Hazardous winter driving conditions are expected Thursday night. This snow is the result of a deepening low pressure system approaching from the southwest. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A couple of significant snowfall events expected. Total snowfall: 5 to 10 cm between Thursday afternoon and Friday morning. 10 to possibly in excess of 25 cm between Friday afternoon and Saturday morning. Maximum wind gusts: 70 km/h or higher Friday night. Locations: Along the coast from Rigolet to Lodge Bay, and all of the interior for the first snow event. Along the coast from Hopedale to Cartwright as well as the interior from Labrador City and Wabush to Upper Lake Melville for the second snow event. Timespan: Thursday afternoon to Friday morning for the first snow event. Friday afternoon to Saturday morning for the second event. Remarks: Snow is expected for a large portion of Labrador beginning Thursday afternoon through to Friday morning and again beginning on Friday afternoon or evening. The snowfall on Friday night is expected to be the more intense and significant of the two events and be accompanied by high winds. Conditions will improve on Saturday. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
